Another trick I learned from an older HN comment is to create a .marks directory in your home directory and then add the following to your .zshrc<p><pre><code>  export MARKPATH=$HOME/.marks

  function jump {
      cd -P $MARKPATH/$1 2>/dev/null || echo &quot;No such mark: $1&quot;
  }

  function mark {
      mkdir -p $MARKPATH; ln -s $(pwd) $MARKPATH/$1
  }

  function unmark {
      rm -if &quot;$MARKPATH/$1&quot;
  }

  function marks {
      ls -l $MARKPATH | sed &#x27;s/  / /g&#x27; | cut -d&#x27; &#x27; -f9- | sed &#x27;s/ -/ -/g&#x27; && echo
  }

  function _marks {
      reply=($(ls $MARKPATH))
  }

  compctl -K _marks jump
  compctl -K _marks unmark
</code></pre>
Now to remember a directory you type<p><pre><code>  % mark <any_string>
</code></pre>
and to jump to that directory you type<p><pre><code>  % jump <any_string>
</code></pre>
To list all your shortcuts<p><pre><code>  % marks
</code></pre>
Depending on the version of ls you might have to change the -f9 parameter to -f8 for marks functions
